      "response": "The State Highway Administration's no. 1 priority is and always has been cars, so no it does not balance that with pedestrian, bicycle or transit needs. It is doing better only because of public and political pressure and because of the problem of pedestrian fatalities. In Prince George's County, the bulk of those fatalities occur on our state roads. SHA should absolutely be charged legislatively with elevating pedestrian and bike safety and it can do so by replicating county efforts around this -- designing complete streets around transit hubs with narrower travel lanes for cars, traffic calming devices like chokers and landscaping and other features that force motorists to slow down and give pedestrians a chance to make safe crossings. This would have to be a legislative mandate as SHA will not do this of its own accord. Even if the leadership now would be amenable to this, with the change of administrations every 4-8 years, future leaders could change course."
