      "response": "I would prioritize these and other projects based on consideration of both standardized and subjective criteria.     Standardized criteria include relative cost and relative projected changes in vehicle miles travelled (VMT), person throughput, travel time improvement, transit mode share and intersection failure. The importance of cost, person throughput and travel time are obvious. Vehicle miles travelled and transit mode share are particularly relevant to environmental considerations (e.g. lowered VMT generally indicates lowered air emissions).  Subjective criteria include perceptions of equity and potential environmental harm that is not as easily subject to standardized comparative measurement.  Standardized and subjective criteria inform funding decisions, but judgment is ultimately required.     M-83 provides an example of how I would apply these criteria to a real world situation.  The Midcounty Corridor Study Supplemental Report dated February 10, 2017 (the Study) compares alternatives for improving travel between the Clarksburg area and the Shady Grove area. The report compares three scenarios to a no-build scenario.  Scenario 1 consists of BRT on route 355 plus certain intersection improvements and road widenings. Scenario 2 consists of BRT on Route 355 plus a new reversible 2 lane road generally referred to as M-83, and Scenario 3 consists of a 4 lane non-reversible version of M-83 without BRT.     The people of Clarksburg have been promised improvement in down-County travel through various planning documents and statements by planners and elected leaders over the years. Thus, as a matter of equity and consistent with other priorities, transportation improvement is warranted.     Table  2-2 of the Study compares the performance of Scenarios 1, 2 and 3 across standardized criteria other than cost. It shows that Scenarios 1 and 2 are roughly comparable with each other in travel time improvement (depending upon where one lives), transit mode share and intersection failure.  Scenario 2 has better person throughput, and Scenario 1 has better VMT.  However, going beyond the Study, Scenario 2 would result in new crossings of sensitive stream valleys and wetlands and is projected to cost roughly twice as much as Scenario 1. On balance, therefore, Scenario 1 seems to be the best choice for improving transportation between Clarksburg and the Shady Grove area."
