      "response": "It is not my understanding that call-up has been struck down by the Court of Appeals. Call-up has been used appropriately, and on occasion and has been abused. My experience with call-up as a citizen and as a councilmember has generally been positive. Generally, it is a helpful tool that can compensate for the lack of familiarity of citizens with the planning and zoning process.     There appears to be a misconception about who call-up should advantage. If the applicant is dissatisfied with the planning board or zoning hearing examiner decision, the applicant's zoning attorney files an appeal. There is no need for a call-up. On the other hand, for opponents, a variety of situations occur that lead to their failure to present a complete case  or any case. In these instances, call-up arguably is appropriate to address the inherent power imbalance in land-use matters.     Call-up has been criticized by the planning board and staff, and by developers. The developers complain about it because it gives citizens who are not familiar with the process the opportunity to be heard when they have failed to become aware of a matter in a timely fashion. Developers complain about lack of certainty, but citizens complain about being seriously disadvantaged in zoning matters in multiple ways. GGW members are generally engaged in land use policy, but such is not the case for average residents. Having served as an attorney for civic associations and individual citizens in land use matters for many years, I am well aware of the lack of knowledge of most residents. And, while there is not an exact correlation, the ability to engage fairly in a land use matter tends to diminish in communities of lower income or a higher degree of immigrants.     With regard to planning board and staff complaints, I respect the concerns of the staff that good planning can be undermined by call-up. However, this ignores other realities of the land use process.     First, the planning board members are appointed by the County Executive traditionally have been very pro-development with limited concern for community impact. For much of the past 15 years, the planning board chair has been a developer attorney. Virtually no citizen in a major case believes that they get a fair hearing before the planning board.     Second, while Prince George's County often has excellent planning staff, it is known that staff is often pressured by the planning department administration to make concessions. This practice undermines arguments that call-up leads to bad planning. Administrative interference also leads to bad planning. This point should be evident in the bad, sprawl development that is strewn around the County. Of course, County Council interference can also hurt. County Council interference occurs in multiple ways (e.g., site-specific text amendments) that are unrelated to the call-up mechanism. As stated above, call-up can be positive or negative.     Third, with respect to specific applications, the planning process involves a number of meetings between staff and applicant representatives. Many compromise decisions are made  to the exclusion of the public. The planning board overwhelmingly supports these compromise positions when residents show up at the planning board hearing. Again, the planning process is not perfect, and is sometimes unfair.     Fourth, with respect to the zoning rewrite project, the principal proponents of retaining call-up are experienced and engaged civic activists --- precisely for the reasons listed above. Apart from their experience with bad planning board decisions, these activists are very concerned about having been stripped of their standing rights. The General Assembly recently changed the standing rules, at the request of developers, such that the ability of citizens to appeal to the District Council is seriously undermined. Thus, call-up may be the only mechanism to get a case before the District Council in the future."
