      "response": "I support some but not all of the changes set forth in the city's proposed Comprehensive Plan. I've seen density be both a positive and negative force in our city's development. Therefore, I want the new Comp Plan to be clearer with regards to the Zoning Commission's powers. This new Comp Plan has loosened density definitions and determined that the Zoning Commission should interpret provisions as a suggestion, as opposed to a requirement. This places the Commission's opinion and authority above the intention of the legislation.      I'm interested in keeping housing affordable for existing owners.  One way to do this is to build enough affordable housing stock to hold down housing inflation and lessen the amount of rent increases that landlords can impose. We can also expand tax deferral programs for seniors.    I support higher density around existing Metrorail stations to ensure that we are making Washington efficiently and effectively planned.  While, as you know, more developable land is on the eastern half of the District, there is no reason why Wards 2, 3, 4 and 6 should not contribute to planned and proposed affordable housing.    I think developing a stronger right of return or more generous buyout requirements for tenants in affordable housing locations being redeveloped would be a good idea.  There should be time limits on developers providing the redeveloped housing units, and non- compliance should incur financial penalties that flow to the displaced tenants."
