      "response": "I am in favor of the District's efforts to implement sustainable ways to transport our residents quickly, efficiently, and safely throughout our city streets. Actions that improve bicycle safety in downtown DC that also support efficient automobile movement are consistent with this goal. Protected bicycle lanes improve the environment and the local economy, and they provide a safer means of travel for cyclists, motorists and pedestrians alike.  Protected bicycle lanes have a high cost-benefit ratio, and provide multiple benefits. Significantly, on streets with protected bicycle lanes, bicycle riders suffer up to 90% fewer injuries. Bicycle lanes slow automobile traffic to safer speeds, and get bicycles off of sidewalks where they endanger children, the elderly, and others.  Protected bicycle lanes improve safety for motorists who no longer need to cross into the oncoming traffic lane to avoid bicyclists. The additional space improves drivers' ability to navigate and make quick stops. Motorists are also able to travel at a more consistent speed without the need to slow down for cyclists.  Finally, as District residents would feel safer biking in protected bicycle lanes and encourage more residents to ride bicycles. That said, I also firmly support more accountability among the District's bicycle riding population. While certainly the vast majority of District bicyclists obey District laws and ride safely, some bicyclists flagrantly ignore common sense bicycle rules and regulations, endangering themselves, motorists, and pedestrians. I therefore also support increased fines for violations of traffic laws, and enhanced enforcement of those laws. Finally, I strongly support District policies and programs to encourage all District bicyclist to register their bicycles on the voluntary bicycle registration system administered by the National Bike Registry. By registering their bicycles law enforcement officials are able to access the database to allow for greater success in recovering stolen bicycles.  I also support dedicated bus lanes during morning and evening rush hours, which can reduce District commuters' travel time by millions of hours. Dedicated bus lanes can improve the quality of life in the District by saving travel time, improving traffic safety, reducing greenhouse gases (GHG) and local air pollutant emissions, and increasing physical activity. Dedicated bus lanes reduce asthma and other respiratory problems by reducing air pollution.  In streets with high travel demand, dedicated bus lanes can help move people quickly and provide a viable alternative to individual cars. Dedicated bus lanes separate buses from mixed traffic, which would allow them to travel more quickly throughout the District. Pre-paid boarding and level platforms  similar to those of a metro station rather than the traditional bus stop, facilitate passenger boarding, while traffic signal management that prioritizes buses in dedicated lanes minimizes wait times.  The incorporation of modern fuel efficiency technologies into buses in dedicated bus lanes also contributes to lower fuel consumption and emissions. New state-of-the-art hybrid buses that reduce travel times by 30% means improved air quality and reducing air pollution that causes asthma and other respiratory illnesses.  Dedicated bus lanes are a cleaner, and more efficient mode of transport. Dedicated bus lanes can shorten a 45 minute bus ride into a 30 minute bus ride, which saves time and money for District riders. Dedicated bus lanes would offer District residents a competitive, reliable alternative to individual automobiles, reducing household transportation costs, thereby freeing up more resources for other necessities such as housing and healthcare."
