      "response": "\\tI support a dedicated funding stream for Metro.  \\tIn general, I don't believe the current governance structure is functional. It may have been originally designed to maximize stakeholder participation by the funding jurisdictions, but in practice it has led to paralysis and regional factionalism. I would like to see a smaller and more empowered board.   \\tI am a strong supporter of organized labor, and I would not back a dedicated funding stream unless the increase in dollars for capital expenditures carried provisions limiting cuts to employee pensions and benefits. Metro is a public good, not a private company, and we need to make it whole by funding it properly, not by mimicking corporate profit maximization tactics and taking all the cost savings on the back of workers. The human error element of Metro's Safety track record will not be improved by making employment at WMATA less attractive.  \\tHow to pay for it? I am a supporter of the proposal advanced by Delegate Korman and Senator Feldman in the 2018 session of the General Assembly (HB0372, SB0227) to establish a dedicated fund account in the Transportation Trust Fund, and mandating a prior year base plus 3% floor in the capital budget. The current proposal would direct $125 million/year from the  Motor Vehicle Excise Tax into the new Metro fund in the TTF for grants to WMATA capital needs, and would also raise the total dollars in the capital budget to around $175 million by 2023 - as opposed to ~$155 million projected today. The fiscal note for the bills projects a huge hit to the overall capital funds ($1.2 billion for the five years starting in FY19) for MDOT as a result of this, based on the fact that the $125 million diverted to Metro would reduce the pledgeable tax revenue that the department can use to secure bond issues. However I disagree with some of the analysis. For one thing, there seems to be an implicit assumption in their numbers that interest rates will rise and the bond market will tighten. More importantly, the analysis uses MDOT's conservative management practice for how it calculates its coverage ratio. The statutory requirement is that revenue and pledged taxes for a given FY must equal 2.0 times the total debt service on all outstanding future obligations that year. But in practice, MDOT requires pledgeable income to be 2.5 times outstanding obligations. It's not that I object to prudent fiscal management, but I think the reality is for a priority as important as funding Metro, we could easily instruct a reduction in practice to at least a 2.2 to 1  ratio without jeopardizing our AAA bond rating, and that alone would significantly soften the projected shortfall to borrowing capacity. What I'm saying is the fiscal note writers are erring on the side of caution and it's creating too much doom and gloom around this very reasonable proposal."
