      "question": "Do you think the current accessory dwelling process is working well? Do you support the County Board's recent changes? Would you expand it to allow converting existing garages or other structures? What other changes would you make?",
      "response": "Simply put, an Accessory Dwelling Unit (ADU) is a second dwelling unit with a kitchen, bathroom and separate entrance on a single-family lot. The Affordable Housing Master Plan appropriately recognizes ADUs as another tool to expand affordable housing opportunities without public subsidies and facilitate additional homeowner income and aging in place. While the County has had an ADU ordinance since 2009, only 20 have been built, and I backed the process to reconsider the various restrictions on ADU's that have inhibited their creation.     Action taken by the County Board in November 2017 greatly expands the potential for the creation of new ADU's, but I view the Board's action as a mixed bag. While I fully supported the proposal to remove size limits on ADU's contained wholly within the basement of an existing home, and am pleased with provisions to require owner occupancy of either the main dwelling or the ADU, I am uncomfortable with the Board's vote to allow conversion of existing (as of our November 2017 adoption date) outside accessory buildings to accessory dwelling use for structures like garages that may literally be just one foot from a neighbor's property line. Having a garage, a shed, or other uninhabited structure one foot from someone's property line is one thing--facilitating the creation of a habitable dwelling for up to three unrelated people with the attendant potential for noise, light and movement, and the loss of privacy, at all hours of the day and night, is another proposition entirely--and one that I believe needed more analysis and community engagement.      I was pleased that the Board did defer legalization of newly erected (after November 2017) detached ADU's in order to examine such issues as appropriate setback requirements, but it is also imperative that we examine the environmental implications and potential loss of tree canopy that would surely come with new freestanding backyard structures of up to 750 square feet with attendant foundations and other structural and operational necessities like plumbing and other utilities.    Finally, I was disappointed that the Board decided not to adopt a key recommendation of our Planning Commission--to limit the creation of new ADU's to 200 per year. This cap seemed reasonable to me as a way of reassuring the community that single family neighborhoods would not be suddenly overrun with new housing units and the accompanying implications for parking, traffic, schools and community infrastructure. In addition, under the revised ordinance, a homeowner could convert an ADU into accessory homestay use  (i.e., AirBnB), with a simple County permit, thus doing nothing to actually boost the supply of modestly priced housing that is intended by the new legislation. The Board should have started with the 200 annual limit proposed by the Planning Commission, a limit that could always be adjusted. Why not take the time to assess the full consequences of ADU's and manage their growth in a deliberate manner?"
