      "response": "I was pleased to join my Board colleagues three years ago in unanimous adoption of the ambitious AHMP. Since that time, I have supported a number of concrete steps to implement the document. Just in calendar year 2017, the Board unanimously voted to add 598 units of new housing for low-and-moderate income households through $30 million in Affordable Housing Investment Fund (AHIF) loans, which loans are funded both by County monies and developer contributions.      Working with our non-profit affordable housing developers, the Board approved substantial rehabilitation of the Berkeley on South Glebe Road, new construction of a mixed-use project at the Central United Methodist Church site in Ballston, and an acquisition loan for the Park Shirlington Apartments.     In February 2018, we unanimously approved funding for a new 12-story affordable project in the heart of RosslynQueens Court.    At my urging, the AHMP strengthened requirements for greater geographic distribution of affordable housing projects throughout the County, and I was especially pleased to advocate for the rescue of 68 units in the Westover community off Washington Boulevard, just a few blocks from my house.    At the same time, it is important to recognize that AHIF funding is finite, and we need to be more creative and resourceful in working towards greater housing affordability. To this end, last year I supported the Board's adoption of reduced parking guidelines for new residential developments in the Metro corridors. I also believe that the County must consider a number of potential strategies for reducing costs and expanding resources to meet the production goals of the AHMP as described in Fulfilling the Promise, a December 2017 document presented to the County Board by an array of for-profit and nonprofit developers and affordable housing groups.      With my support, County staff is now examining the feasibility of a number of recommendations in the report, including (a) reducing site plan conditions for new affordable housing construction, (b) waiving or reducing certain permit and tap fees for such projects, (c) overhauling use permit conditions for rehabilitation projects, (d) modernizing the development process for smaller sites, and (e) offering property tax abatements or exemptions.    Potential revenue ideas that may have merit include increased dedicated recordation tax and special purpose general obligation bonds.    Finally, we can't lose sight of the fact that the AHMP is not just about housing production. Important Master Plan goals we need to make a reality include (a) ensuring equal housing access through enforcement of Arlington's Human Rights ordinance, the Fair Housing Act and other laws, as well as through housing vouchers, home ownership assistance, displacement assistance, and homeless prevention, (b), enabling Arlingtonians to age in place through real estate tax relief and other programs and services geared to seniors, and (c) ensuring that our housing efforts contribute toward fiscal and environmental sustainability through rigorous property code enforcement, physical inspections, financial monitoring and audits, and environmental standards."
