      "response": "As someone who lives in the Tara-Leeway Heights community, I appreciate Lee Highwayjust blocks awayboth for its diverse array of neighborhood retail and services as well as its value as a multi-modal commuter thoroughfare. I often take the ART 55 or the Metrobus 3Y to or from the East Falls Church Metro Station and points in between, or, in the case of the 3Y, to and from the District.    While the County Manager has proposed a slowdown in comprehensive planning for Lee Highway in order to fulfill County Board direction to avoid another property tax rate increase this year, I am committed to seeing the Lee Highway planning process continue as expeditiously as possible. A future Lee Highway can further contribute to the economic competitiveness and tax base of Arlington County through realization of its promise as a vibrant, pedestrian-friendly and inclusive community where people of all incomes can live, work and be at leisure.    We expect to provide continued funding to the non-profit Lee Highway Alliance again this year, a true, grassroots-neighborhood and business-oriented nonprofit that facilitates the great variety of voices and stakeholders flanking the corridor. A Request for Proposals (RFP) has been recently let for a consultant to assist with the next stage of the planning process, including the scope of work, major milestones and work products, and a roadmap for civic engagement. The County will convene the official project kick-off with community stakeholders once the full team is in place before 2018 is out.    I believe that it makes good planning sense to introduce additional, but sensitively-placed, mixed use density along Lee Highway, particularly near the main commercial nodes. Any such added density should taper down adjacent to the neighborhoodsa central tenet of Arlington's planning principles. Yet the plethora of commercial property owners and the relative shallowness of many sites eligible for commercial redevelopment will make this a challenge. We should consider a streamlined, less costly site plan process to incentivize such redevelopment.  But no one wants to see the Clarendonization of Lee Highway or the wholesale loss of its many one-of-a-kind restaurants and businesses, many of which are owned or operated by our newest Americans.    Finally, we need to recognize that Lee Highway is controlled by the state and is a major evacuation route.   While more intensified bus service may be needed as population and density increase over time, I do not now see traffic lane reconfiguration or bicycle lanes as safe and viable options. As I observe in response to the Columbia Pike question below, any multimodal improvements must be calibrated to avoid the unfortunate byproduct of encouraging traffic diversion onto nearby neighborhood streets."
