      "response": "I am running for Prince George's County Executive because it's time to jumpstart the next era of opportunity for our neighbors through key investments in innovation, development, education, and an accountable and responsive County Government.     I believe we have a solid framework for an innovation corridor that can propel our local economy in the 21st Century.  I will work to leverage our County's tech corridor of the University of Maryland, Bowie State College, Prince George's Community College, Goddard Space Flight Center, and the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration to grow an innovation economy here in Prince George's that can serve as a hub for a whole new generation of start-up businesses -- the next I-270 corridor   with the right investments.    To grow the innovation economy in Prince George's, it is essential that we transform our education system and make transit-oriented development a cornerstone of our economic development future.    As a former analyst and project engineer in the space program as well as a former chair of the United States House of Representatives' Space Subcommittee, I understand and value the hidden technology secret of Prince George's County  we need to tell our story and invest in innovation incubators for cybersecurity, aerospace, earth science and other technologies. And, we have the tools to do just that.    Prince George's County is the birthplace of smart growth.  I was proud to receive the leadership award from the Coalition for Smarter Growth, Sierra Club, and the Landscape Architects Association for my work to try to bring rail over the Wilson Bridge, funding for the Purple Line, championing transit-oriented development, green infrastructure development for wastewater systems, and other work to create livable, walkable, workable communities.    But the reality of transit-oriented development in the County has not met our aspirations because of too little focus, perceptions of a pay-to-play culture, and the misdirection of public investment into wasteful spending on new highways in places far away from job centers, transit, established neighborhoods, and public facilities (be it schools, libraries, parks, or community centers).    Accelerating transit-oriented development (TOD) in Prince George's will require shifting public investment towards new transportation priorities  for example, simply choosing to not fund ONE of our recent sprawling, highway expansion projects in Brandywine, Konterra, or Westphalia could have created the equivalent of a $40-60 million capital fund to support the kind of streetscape improvements, pedestrian/bicycle safety initiatives, public facilities, and placemaking that could help more neighborhoods -- including the priority TOD sites of Branch Avenue, Largo Town Center, New Carrollton, and Suitland to grow into regional destinations anchored by existing transportation infrastructure (building upon the momentum created by the initial success that College Park, Hyattsville, and the Gateway Arts District have achieved in establishing the County's first walkable urban places)."
