      "question": "Do you support dedicated, bondable funding for Metro totaling at least $500 million a year including at least $167 million from Maryland? How would you achieve this and what funds would you use? Do you require other steps (governance, labor, etc.) before you can support it?",
      "response": "Metro is a major contributor to our region's economic success. Not only is it critical for moving hundreds of thousands of people to and from jobs across the region every day. Metro has also been instrumental in supporting placemaking across the region, by encouraging more accessible, walkable communities. That is why, I strongly support dedicated, bondable funding for Metro of at least $500 million a year, including at least $167 million from Maryland.    Similar to what is laid out in the proposed Maryland Metro Funding Act, I would support the creation of a Maryland Metro Dedicated Fund Account within the Transportation Trust Fund with mandatory annual appropriations. While the Maryland Metro Funding Act  would rely on existing revenue collected for the Transportation Fund to support Metro, I would instead advocate for the the creation of a 1 percent  regional sales tax. This regional sales tax could help insulate Metro funding from existing fluctuations to revenue streams that support the Transportation Trust Fund and would make more funding available for other important projects that rely on the Fund.    Given the recent challenges faced by Metro and the perceived lack of accountability, a dedicated funding stream can only be successful if taxpayers feel like that money is being used as effectively as possible and is improving the system. That is why I support making several reforms to the existing WMATA Compact to increase accountability. First, I would support a strengthening of  the Office of Inspector General with mandated funding and through increased auditing and staffing decision authority. I would also support strengthening the existing Riders Advisory Council by mandating dedicated funds for its operation and by allowing local jurisdictions to appoint representatives, rather than appointments being determined by WMATA's application process. Metro should also be required to regularly update their strategic plans, something that is already done on an ad hoc basis, and provide ample opportunity for public comment."
