      "response": "I do not support Governor Hogan's splashy but substance-free proposal to expand I-495, I-270, and the BW Parkway. Decades of experience shows us that building more highways can hollow out communities while only leading to more traffic due to induced demand. For this reason, I think transit expansions would instead be a much better use of limited state funds. My priorities specifically would be all-day, two-way MARC service, an infill MARC station in the White-Flint area, and true bus-rapid transit viathe Corridor Cities Transitway, Route 29, and Route 355. I have been a consistent supporter of BRT in Montgomery County, most recently advocating for a study of the BetterBRT plan for 29.    That is all not to say that we should not invest in roadways when appropriate. I, however, would want to make sure that existing repairs are prioritized before adding even more infrastructure. Any additional freeway lanes should come from repurposing existing median space, not widening; I would like to see that new lane space devoted to dedicated transit, such as bus-rapid transit or HOT/HOV lanes. We should be extremely wary of Virginia's model in this regard, where the PPP leading to 66 toll lanes actually forbids expansion of the orange line. I would vehemently oppose any such deals that hamper transit infrastructure to prioritize roads."
