      "question": "Do you think the State Highway Administration appropriately balances walking, bicycling, car, and transit needs or does it favor fast car movement to the exclusion of other needs? Would you support changes to SHA oversight and policies to make streets safer for walking and biking even if it slows down car traffic?",
      "response": "Like so much of the United States, Maryland is a state built to prioritize the car. And the dominance of the car and its role in shaping infrastructure leads to a vicious cycle where the inconveniences created for non-drivers push them to car-transportation, which degrades the constituency for other forms of transportation, leading to further dominance of the car. Breaking that cycle therefore requires government intervention through smart policy development. Such intervention is justified because this is not a mere policing of preferences; a car-dominant transportation infrastructure has many negative side effects for society. From their large, negative impact on the environment to the injury and death attributable to motor accidents, cars provide many reasons to, if not privilege, at least put on equal footing other forms of transportation.     As a result, I would be a strong proponent of steps to reform the State Highway Administration to be sure that it takes seriously the safety and transportation needs of Marylanders traveling on the state's roads using something other than a car. The SHA currently does not take responsibility for maintaining pedestrian pathways next to its roadways or install crosswalks that would allow pedestrians to cross busy streets. In addition to supporting efforts to get SHA do more in these areas, I would also support innovative and effective approaches to improving pedestrian and bike safety and convenience through traffic control efforts such as HAWK signals and enhanced protections for pedestrians and bikers in crosswalks.     Cars are not going away entirely anytime soon in most of Montgomery County and Maryland. But where we can make it easier and faster to move people (rather than focusing on moving automobiles specifically) we should. It is better for the environment, better for cyclists and transit users, and better for drivers who will have less competition on the roads.  "
