      "response": "Would you like to see Maryland, Virginia, and DC collaborate to avoid a race to the bottom? How does your approach shape your views on regional projects like Metro, Amazon's HQ2 bid, and a possible new NFL stadium?    Though like many who are hopeful that our region can be a leader in smart development and a strong supporter of reinvesting in our public institutions, I am as concerned about the potential for a race to the bottom dynamic on both a national and local level when it comes to attracting major projects that will affect the area. That said, especially in the Amazon HQ2, I also think they provide a unique and unusual opportunity to galvanize public support around investing in our area. For that reason, I think that we should build our way to being a competitive region to attract external investment, as in HQ2. Amazon (and most knowledge-economy corporations looking to expand) want locations near transit; they want diverse and skilled workers; and they want good schools for their employees' kids. We all want those things, and our efforts should focus on strengthening our area's fundamentals.  And to make sure these efforts strengthen our entire region, I also strongly support working together with other parts of the region to make these investments strategically and in ways that complement one another -- because if any jurisdiction in our area wins Amazon, we all win. In general, though, we should be committing ourselves to investing in schools, especially early childhood education, and transit infrastructure that can not only handle the new influx of residents that would be implied by Amazon moving to our area, but also make sure that it does so at a level that is competitive with the most effective transit systems in the country and world. We should also strive to make housing in the area more affordable so that relocation to the area is an attractive place to stay for new workers who come to the area as a result of new investment.     The same spirit of collaboration is of course also true for Metro, as a successful Metro system will be key to attracting new and valuable development to the area. A system that serves the area effectively and extensively can not only improve the experiences of all residents but also improve the economies across the region.     Though I would generally like to see government get out of the stadium subsidy game altogether, I recognize that there is strong regional support for our sports teams and that the regional cohesion that collective interest provides also should not be overlooked. Nevertheless, I have a few priorities in this regard. First, I would prefer such projects not to take place in areas that could be put to better use with high density housing or building of other sorts, as in the case of RFK stadium and it's long overdue demolition. Second, where such stadium projects do go forward, it's important to recognize that these publicly subsidized projects often result in private benefits. As a result, any publicly funded stadium project should be designed for mixed-use and not just devoted to a single team or sport and otherwise left dormant."
