      "response": "There is a great need for reducing traffic congestion but I do not support the expansion of the highway lanes in the manner that the Governor has proposed. There are better ways to solve the problem and to do so quickly.      That is why I would require a new transportation planning process and assessment of alternatives overall.      The first thing I would do is ensure that modern Transit System Management (TSM) and the interactive traffic signals and other systems it includes are in place on every state highway or road with any significant congestion.  The top ten such intersections in Montgomery County are north to south but the State rejected a Tiger Grant from the Federal Transit Administration for TSM on East to West routes near Washington and asked that it be reprogrammed to help renovate and expand a transit station that had gone over budget.    Once TSM is in place, we'll then need to expand clean, safe non-rail transit systems, which are much less capital intensive and more flexible in terms of routes and responding to ridership demand as it unfolds in the real world.  Then we'll need to carefully assess the alternatives for more expensive investments in all respects and there is a process for doing that right.  Key performance and financing considerations are included in the Federal Highway Act and related laws but they are not well enforced and are likely to be less well enforced as the Trump Administration proposes to waive or weaken Federal law in the Infrastructure bill.  That could result in massive spending on poorly planned projects.  The existing federal standards should be upheld and augmented by Maryland as we can afford the highest quality and we know how to achieve it without over-spending."
