      "response": "Income inequality in the District is a significant concern of mine.  As I see it, there are a number of root causes that we must get serious about addressing.      First off, we have to start educating our children to be prepared for the jobs of the future.  We have to end the destructive process of \"teaching to the test\", teaching children with the goal of getting them to score high enough on standardized tests to give the impression that our education system is working.  As has recently come to light in a series of disturbing news stories, we are pushing students to graduation without providing them with a true education.  After they graduate from high school they are ill prepared to succeed in college and they have no employable skills.  We need to reinstate vocational training in our public schools, and not woodshop, a class I took in Junior High School decades ago, but vocation training in the information technology field so students who don't off to college can find meaningful work in D.C. now in the 21st Century.  For those students who do opt for the college route, we need to be sure that when they graduate from high school they are prepare to compete in any college or university in this nation.  We need to make sure they are getting a well rounded education, including art, music, science, social sciences and financial literacy.  Education is the new currency of the 21st Century (a quote from radio personality Joe Madison).  Our young people need their fare share of that currency if they are going to lead our city in closing the income gap.           Second, we need to strengthen and enforce our First Source law.  There is too much development in our city for there to be so many unemployed residents.  Granted, part of the problem lies in the fact that too many of our residents don't have the skills or education to make them eligible for the high end jobs associated with such development.  Nevertheless, it is inexcusable that District residents are so poorly represented on construction projects, even, it appears, in so-called unskilled positions.  Perhaps a carrot and stick approach is needed.  We should penalize developers who skirt or First Source requirements but we should also incentivize those who go above and beyond it minimum requirements.    Third, we should consider the fact that part of our unemployment and underemployment problem stems from the fact that too many of our residents have permanent criminal records even though they may have paid their debt to society many years ago and lived a crime free life ever since.  D.C. has a law which provides for the sealing of criminal records but that law lists about 40 categories of criminal offenses which are ineligible for expungement or sealing no matter how long it has been since conviction.  Many of the crimes in those categories are for what most would consider rather minor offenses.  I believe we need to revisit that law and make it easier for persons who have made an honest effort at rehabilitation and kept their noses clean for a number of years to have their records sealed.  Ban the box legislation, which prohibits a prospective employer from inquiring about a job applicant's criminal record until a conditional offer of employment is made is not enough.  Citizens who have paid their debt to society and demonstrated good citizenship ought not be relegated to a state of permanent unemployability due to a mistake made years ago.    Fourth, we have to look closely at our minimum wage law (to make sure it provides for a livable minimum wage), parental leave, increased child care tax credits and other policies that help to prevent low income earnings from slipping into homelessness.  As quiet as it's kept, every homeless person is not unemployed.  We must have policies in place that ensure that every working person has the ability to obtain and maintain a safe place to call home.  That loops back into the topic of affordable housing but it incorporates a broader discussion of the social safety net and what role the District ought to play in that regard.    Finally, homelessness can stem from several root causes, chief among them unemployment, underemployment, and depression and other mental health issues.   We need to provide safe, clean shelters for the homeless.  It is a very sad commentary that some chronically homeless people would rather face extremely adverse conditions on the street than to go into District run or supported homeless shelters because of the realistic fear that in those shelters ,they might be assaulted, have their few possessions stolen, or both.   We must strengthen our outreach to the homeless community by making an effort to determine why they are on the streets and by providing mental health assistance where needed.  And we must ensure that people with mental health issues are identified and given the assistance they need rather than admitted into shelters where, without adequate support and supervision, they can pose a clear and present danger to themselves and others.  I believe that business and government partnerships and collaborations could be developed to address the problems of homelessness.  We should look closely at incentives that the District might provide to business to solicit their support in this important effort."
