      "response": "One of the most pressing issues we have right now in the District is a mismatch between our workforce and the jobs that are being created. There are good jobs with real career paths available, but our residents are not being prepared for them. DCPS students being passed through high school and graduated without the skills to succeed in the world is at the heart of this problem. Many of our adults struggle with basic literacy and numeracy. Adult education programs such as Academy of Hope work to address this issue, but it's clearly a failure of our most basic system  public education. I supported the increase in the minimum wage, and that will help. But it takes more than $15 an hour, 40 hours per week to support a family in the District of Columbia. We need to fix this issue in our schools, and do all we can to train the adults we failed when they were in public schools. One of the career paths I've championed on the Council is the Clean Teams. I've established several in Ward 1 and added new positions each year. I love this program because it helps employ people who have struggled to find work, including formerly incarcerated residents, and gives them the chance to move up quickly. It also keeps our commercial corridors clean and safe. We should continue adding Clean Teams around the District.    The cost of living in a city as prosperous as DC is only going to go up. While we are doing the work of better preparing our workforce for careers we need to continue doing all we can to offset the cost of housing. I've worked to preserve and produce more than 500 units of affordable housing in Ward 1 (at 30%, 50% and 80% AMI, but with a strong focus at 50% and below) since I took office three years ago. Preservation is key here, because we cannot build fast enough for the need. The other major investment we've made, that I've supported, is our Local Rent Supplement Program, which gives residents rent vouchers to subsidize existing housing such that they are only paying one third of their income in rent.     As chair of the Committee on Human Services, preventing homelessness and strengthening the District's homelessness emergency services are a major focus of my work. Working with a coalition of providers and residents, I recently reformed the decade-old Homeless Services Act to preserve the District's right to shelter while ultimately strengthening our emergency homeless services. The reforms will allow us to move more families into housing and out of shelter. I also passed landmark reform of the District's Temporary Assistance to Needy Families program, which provides cash assistance to hundreds of very low-income District families. The reform keeps families from being cut off and permanently protects assistance for children. It offers more cash assistance without a time limit placed on each family, which will prevent homelessness.     Housing First has been the homelessness policy in the District for several years now, with the belief that helping families find stability in their own home will allow us to better serve their underlying needs, whether they be job readiness, mental health or family conflict. In FY2018 I moved nearly $8 million into housing programs  hundreds of units of Permanent Supportive Housing and Targeted Affordable Housing. I also invested in our Homelessness Prevention Program, which partners families at risk with local organizations like Community of Hope, and helps them stabilize before they become homeless. I also funded the newly launched plan to end youth homelessness, Solid Foundations, in the FY2018 budget. Breaking the cycle of homelessness early can help prevent chronic homelessness. Additionally, I supported adding $100 million each year to the District's Housing Production Trust Fund, which is used to build affordable housing.     The District has a plan to end homelessness called Homeward DC. We must fully fund it in order to eradicate homelessness. While family homelessness is a problem that we will not solve until we address the affordable housing and workforce challenges we face, chronic homelessness is absolutely solvable. By investing in Permanent Supportive Housing, we can get people off the street and help them thrive."
