      "response": "I have read in detail the Technical Panel Final Report on Metro dated April 2017 as well as former Secretary LaHood's reports, both of which concurred on the need for additional funding to ensure capital and maintenance funding, but I cannot accept any of the recommendations in the Technical Panel report on funding sources.      Looking at the proposed budget for WMATA for the next ten years (Page 37 of the final report), the revenue generated from all sources (primarily passenger fees) is only $9.34 billion dollars, while the expected state and local subsidies account for $10.75 billion dollars.  This is before putting in place the additional dedicated funding request of approximately $650 million per year ($6.5 billion total over 10 years) that a 1% sales tax would generate.  If the sales tax is put into effect, it would mean that revenues from WMATA metro and bus sales would only account for about one-third of total funding.  While a public transport system can be subsidized by the government, it must also make economic sense to run the system, meaning that fares, capital improvement projects, and expenses have to be grounded in reality in order to keep Metro viable.  The report also makes it clear that increased funding would be needed in perpetuity and hints at other critical capital projects that would be needed, beyond those currently identified, that could require even further investment.  It would be irresponsible to place so much of the burden on running the system on only the counties nearest to the Metro through the sales tax.    The approach I would take is to ask our congressional delegation to reach out to the federal government.  The federal government has a special responsibility to support the system given high utilization of Metro by federal employees and by millions of yearly visitors to the Capital, and I would ask our representatives to build on US Rep. Barbara Comstock's WMATA reform bill, to accept some changes in the governance of the WMATA (i.e. instituting a reform board), but changing the bill so more funds are provided for ongoing capital investments (than the current 75 million per year) and by moderating some of the unhelpful language against labor unions.  If the federal government is willing to increase its investment, then Maryland, Virginia, and the District as a whole (not just the areas closest to Metro) can make the difficult choices needed to prioritize Metro funding."
