      "response": "I am committed to implementing Vision Zero, and I helped lead the Council's efforts to require the County Executive to develop a Vision Zero plan. I strongly believe that our transportation system needs to be redesigned to lower speeds and to ensure that any mistakes made by users do not become deadly. While there is much more to be done and I am not satisfied with the County's progress to date, I have championed numerous reforms that will help get the County to zero deaths by 2030.     Roadways: We need a contemporary road code for the entire county that prioritizes safety for all users and all modes. I have been working on this for several years, and plan to introduce legislation establishing a new road code based on the code developed by Toole Design Group for other local jurisdictions. This new road code will build on the reforms the County achieved when the Council passed my legislation (Bill 33-13 - Urban Road Code) in 2013 that reduced curb radii and lane widths in our urban areas. We also need to budget for road diets.     The County needs significantly more protected bicycle infrastructure so that roads are safe for bicyclists of all ages and all skill levels. We know that more people will ride their bike for trips to transit, shopping, work, entertainment, and recreation if we provide low stress connections to their destination. To this end, I have successfully secured new funding for protected bicycle infrastructure in Silver Spring and White Flint and now Bethesda. In this year's capital budget (FY19-FY24), I will be fighting for new funds to build protected bicycle infrastructure in Wheaton, Gaithersburg, and many other areas of the County.      Law: We need the State of Maryland to agree to our vision for Vision Zero and support its implementation on State roads in Montgomery County. For example, last year I pushed for bills in the State legislature to give the County authority to lower speed limits on county roads below 25 mph. While that effort unfortunately did not succeed, I will try again next year hopefully this time with the active support of a stronger Vision Zero coalition. Further, I vigorously supported State legislation in 2017 that would have allowed Maryland DOT to use HAWK signals on State Highways. As a result of the pressure from the legislation and strong local advocacy, Maryland DOT agreed to install a HAWK-like signal at the intersection of Veirs Mill Rd. and Turkey Branch Parkway (Matthew Henson Trail).     DOT practices: For far too long the State and, and to a lesser extent, the County DOT have prioritized motor vehicle traffic flow to the detriment of pedestrian and bicyclist safety. Although both agencies have made improvements recently, larger changes to the mindset and culture are required. The road code changes I mentioned above will codify a better culture top-to-bottom. More specifically, I believe that the County and State DOT need to be much more aggressive in their use of innovative traffic calming measures, speed signs and cameras, and pedestrian activated signals (ie. HAWK signals). I look forward to advocating for these measures and providing our County DOT with sufficient resources to accomplish our collective Vision Zero goals."
